Ille, datis vadibus, &c. ‘⁶ He, who, having given bail for his appearance, has been forced from the country into the city.'’ The allusion is to the defendant in a suit. In the Roman courts of law, as in our own, the plaintiff required that tho defendant should give bail for his appearance in court, (vades,) on a certain day, which was usually the third day after. Hence the plaintiff was said vadari reum, and the defendant vades dare, or vadimonium promittere. ——14. Fabium.
